I have created `hypothesis.md` and `candidate.py` based on the hypothesis that people judge randomness using the absolute number of heads, but their penalty for each additional head grows quadratically.

This provides a direct refinement of `iter0_candidate0` (which had a linear penalty) by exploring the opposite non-linear functional form (supra-linear/quadratic penalty) compared to the logarithmic one proposed by `iter1_candidate0`. 

The PyMC model appropriately uses the `pm.Data` tensor directly in the `observed=` argument of the `Bernoulli` likelihood, properly sets a prior on `tau`, and clamps the output probabilities using `pt.clip` for rigorous numerical safety.
